03256nam a22004575i 9780773572225DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20052005xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735722257 a10.1515/97807735722252doi  a(DE-B1597)654862  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPR9185.6.I5bG76 2004eb 7aLCO0060002bisacsh04a810.9/3529971 aGroening, Laura Smyth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aListening to Old Woman Speak :bNatives and alterNatives in Canadian Literature /cLaura Smyth Groening. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (216 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Indigenous and Northern Studies ;v4400tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tListening to Old Woman Speak -- tWriting “Indians” and the Manichean Allegory -- tRepresentation and Identification -- t“A Curiosity … Natural and Feminine” -- t“Poor Creatures, Once so Benighted” -- tInhabiting a Manichean World View -- tAdministering/Ministering to the Indians -- tThe Temptations of Rudy Wiebe -- t“Contamination as Literary Strategy” -- t“Children of Two Peoples”: Hybrid Texts, Hybrid People? -- tThe Healing Aesthetic of Basil H. Johnston -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGroening argues that what Frantz Fanon terms the "manichean allegory" has shaped European understanding of the New World to such an extent that the image patterns fundamental to the allegory continue to dominate depictions of Native characters. Although a world separated into two categories defined by light and dark, reason and emotion, mind and body, technology and nature, future and past is no longer also characterized as good and evil, revaluing the tropes has not made them disappear. And without their disappearance, good intentions notwithstanding, nonaboriginal Canadian writers will continue to portray Native characters as part of a dead and dying culture. Groening demonstrates that the real issue cannot be about censorship as censorship involves the abrogation of freedom, and the imagination is never truly free.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Canadian.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780773572225?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773572225423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773572225/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles